When was the last time you heard about KKK having a big influence on economy or politics, or committing a terrorist attack against the minorities? I'm talking real, certified news, no rumors or conspiracy theories. You can not heal if you keep opening the wounds. And if you think that white people don't know what that feels like, remember that numerous European nations have been at some sort of bloody war with each other at some point in history, but, won't you know: ¬† French don't keep making movies about how awful Brits are (or the other way around) because of the Anglo-French wars, which spanned (though, admittedly, with some big "breaks") for six centuries https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-French_War  and British people don't keep making movies about Nazi Germany; every remotely intelligent and educated person in a Western society knows what happened and that it was awful, to say the least... and that all people involved are now dead. Or lets take a look at Asians: Japanese army literally committed a genocide against Chinese civilians in the 1930s, killing over 300 000 people, and not even frikkein China keeps making movies about those few bloodthirsty radicals (and yes, thousands of soldiers are a small percentage considering that Japan has a population of over 120million). Look up the Nanking Massacre. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanking_Massacre The only bigger aminosity (though still overplayed in the media) is probably in Slavic/Balkan countries following the war in 1990s, but that is still relatively recent history and lots of war criminals haven't been prosecuted. Plus, a white slave trade was present throughout the centuries, but Europeans aren't still at war with other European nations or Africans anymore over that, people have moved on.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_slavery  But if you can't or don't want to do all that, may I remind you that the last world country to outlaw slavery was an AFRICAN country, MAURITANIA, in 1981. They were enslaving and selling their own, black people, years after the slavery was abolished in the USA.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mauritania  All the people involved in American slave trade are now dead. KKK has lost most of its power. Even most of the klansmen from 50s, 60s and 70s, when KKK held much more power, are now mostly dead or in prison. And even back then, KKK/racists were mostly present/strong in Southern countries, not the whole USA. Even back in the 19th century, a white man was the first one to rise up and attemp to free the slaves, simply for finding slavery morally wrong and inhuman, and paid with his life for that; have you heard of John Brown?  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Brown_(abolitionist)  And, last but not least, black man was the president of the USA for eight years. It is about time to drop the victim complex, only call out the racism when you actually see it or experience it, and leave KKK in history books. If you want to make a movie with a political or social message, you would be better off focusing on actual, current, important issues (such as climate change, generation bias/ageism, cyberbullying, and an increasing divide between left-wing and right-wing, regardless of the race).  And if you think my post is just propaganda or whining or something, ask yourself this; does reminding yourself of KKK makes you feel any better? When have you, personally, actually fought racism, and in what form? And is racism still the most important issue/danger in your daily lives?

We just need to come to accept---not look to past eras and divide our country even further. I hope this film, instead, turns into a more wholesome tale about how we just need to understand each other--to sit down and talk and realize that we are ALL humans. Period. This cultural trench doesn't need to be any more emphasized by the public media nowadays, as it frankly encourages us to view the "other side" as nearly foreign, which makes it easier to lack sympathy or understanding for that "other side." This is incredibly dangerous, as it can lead to violence and discrimination, on both sides. We simply need to work out our issues with one another, and that starts by merging the two races in question in order to reach a common moral premise and living by it: we are ALL humans on this small blue earth, and we are ALL equal. Increased racial acceptance does not come by drawing upon such prominent differences in viewpoints......

text: I think the film fails to convincingly convey the authenticity of a period piece. It was embarrassingly obvious, like for example the token historic vehicles used in street scenes. I mean every vehicle was a historically preserved perfect shiny Ford Pinto or Chevy Nova, and it was obvious these were historic vehicles garage-kept and waxed regularly. That's not what they looked like in 1971. They were dirty just like everything else. And the props were obvious and blatant, like for example the "NIXON AGNEW' poster in the interior of a Klansman's home. Most important though was the sense of believability was vacant and missing, and yes I'm well aware it's "based on a true story." But that means nothing in the world of filmmaking. and Spike Lee, who was once a great filmmaker, knows that. The director needs to make magic. I just feel Lee didn't do that here, and in fact didn't come close. It's worth mentioning however, the lead actor John David Washington is fascinating. He has his own individual charisma and magnetism, which he clearly inherited from his father but it comes out in a new and unique way. Really the only saving grace fora real disappointment of a film.  The inner torment Adam Driver's character supposedly is going through over his Judaism was revolting and not at all believable. It was a reach for Adam Driver and even more of a reach for Spike Lee, who has a history of not understanding American Jews and caricaturing them in derogatory fashion in his films. It needs to be mentioned because in the film it is the lynchpin connecting the suffering of Blacks with Jews, which is, as the film tries, the supposedly common ground the two lead actors share. But it's just not believable. The struggle of Jewish people is utterly lost on Spike Lee, and this blind spot can be seen quite clearly & painfully in "BlacKkKlansman."  It's bad acting and badly rendered. Only John David Washington made it bearable but even he could not prevent me from walking out early.  Also the soundtrack- was VERY VERY Tarantino with a capital TARANTINO. Without being redundant, it was embarrassingly derivative of Tarantino. The dancing scene with the Cornelius Brothers and the lead actress with her 1970 gold oval tinted glasses felt staged and unnatural. I'm a huge Cornelius Brothers fan and a huge Looking Glass fan too, so when  "Brandy" played I felt it was gratuitous. Easy. And again, very Quentin Tarantino, and not in a kind of sort of complimentary influential way- I'm talking direct theft.
